{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636685"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:33:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:33:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17601"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.91,0.05,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10315"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10015"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24129"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreas has distinct functional regions that serve different physiological roles in digestion and metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main role of the exocrine pancreas?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Release of gut regulatory peptides","Production of digestive enzymes","Synthesis of bile salts","Storage of fat-soluble vitamins","Control of blood glucose levels"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of digestive enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E is the principal function of the exocrine pancreas. The pancreatic acinar cells synthesise and secrete enzymes including trypsinogen, chymotrypsinogen, pancreatic lipase, and amylase. These enzymes are critical for digesting proteins, fats and carbohydrates in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelease of gut regulatory peptides\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes endocrine rather than exocrine pancreatic function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesis of bile salts\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in hepatocytes within the liver\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of fat-soluble vitamins\u003C/strong\u003E - Fat-soluble vitamins are primarily stored in liver and adipose tissue\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControl of blood glucose levels\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by the endocrine pancreas via hormones like insulin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe exocrine pancreas makes up most of the organ\u0027s mass and its secretions are vital for normal digestion and nutrient absorption in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The exocrine pancreas synthesises and secretes digestive enzymes into the small intestine","Pancreatic enzymes are essential for the digestion of proteins, fats and carbohydrates","The pancreatic acinar cells synthesise enzymes as inactive precursors to prevent autodigestion"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"item